<p><strong>5 FAQs on India's Foreign Policy with Sumit Ganguly</strong></p>
<p><strong>Q1: What is the main focus of India's current foreign policy?</strong></p>
<p>A: According to Sumit Ganguly, India's current foreign policy prioritizes balancing relations with major powers, promoting economic growth and security, and expanding its influence in the Indian Ocean region.</p>
<p><strong>Q2: How has India's relationship with China changed?</strong></p>
<p>A: India-China relations have been strained since 2020 due to border disputes in Ladakh. Ganguly notes that India has adopted a "look east" policy, strengthening ties with Japan, Australia, and the United States, to counterbalance China's growing assertiveness.</p>
<p><strong>Q3: What are the challenges India faces in its foreign policy?</strong></p>
<p>A: Ganguly identifies terrorism, cross-border tensions with Pakistan, and managing relations with neighboring countries as key challenges. India also faces the need to balance its economic interests with its foreign policy goals.</p>
<p><strong>Q4: How has India's relationship with the United States evolved?</strong></p>
<p>A: India and the US have strengthened their strategic partnership in recent years, cooperating on counterterrorism, trade, and security. Ganguly highlights the Quadrilateral Security Dialogue (QUAD) as an important mechanism for this partnership.</p>
<p><strong>Q5: What is the future of India's foreign policy?</strong></p>
<p>A: Ganguly predicts that India will continue to focus on its strategic partnerships, maintain a non-aligned stance, and play a more active role in international organizations. He also emphasizes the need for India to develop a coherent foreign policy strategy that aligns with its national interests and aspirations.</p>